Catherine Anenontha in Quebec City, QC, in 1662. Nicolas Durand from Chenommet in Charente, France, married Marie Renouard in Quebec City, QC, in 1665. Pierre Durand <i>dit</i> Desmarchais from Blois in Loir-et-Cher, France, married Jeanne Chartier in Quebec City, QC, in 1673. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Dandurand","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Armand, Henri, Mathieu, Normand, Serge, Yvon.","French: patronymic, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘of’, from <b>Andurand</b>, from a nickname or an old personal name (compare   Durand  ) derived from Old French <i>endurant</i> ‘enduring, patient’.","History: Antoine Dandurand <i>dit</i> Marchàterre from Paris, France, married Marie Vérieu in Sainte-Famille, Île d'Orléans, QC, in 1696."]},{"name":"Duranceau","meanings":["French: from a diminutive of the personal name   Durand   or of its variants   Duran   and   Durant  ."]},{"name":"Bondurant","meanings":["Altered form of French <b>Bondurand</b>: nickname from <i>bon</i> ‘good’ + the personal name   Durand  , literally ‘good Durand’. Compare   Bundren   and   Bundrant  .","History: Jean-Pierre Bondurand from Génolhac in Gard, France, married Anne Faure in Manakin, VA, <i>c.</i> 1708. His name is listed (in the form <i>Bondurant</i>) in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Dorantes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Francisco, Miguel, Carlos, Javier, Luis, Raul, Alvaro, Joaquin, Juan, Ricardo, Roberto.","Spanish: apparently a variant of <b>Durantes</b> or <b>Durántez</b>, patronymics from the old personal name <i>Durant</i>, a variant of   Durand  ."]},{"name":"Durant","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: variant of   Durand  .","English: variant of <b>Darwent</b>, a habitational name from Derwent in Derbyshire (now submerged by the Ladybower Reservoir) or Darwen in Lancashire, both named from rivers called Derwent, or, less frequently, from similarly named rivers in Cumbria, Durham, Northumbria, and Yorkshire, from a Celtic river name meaning ‘river where oak-trees grow abundantly’.","Altered form of French   Doiron  ."]},{"name":"Duran","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, Irish <i>Ó Deoradháin</i> ‘descendant of <i>Deoradhán</i>’, a byname from a diminutive of <i>deoradh</i> ‘pilgrim; stranger, exile’."]},{"name":"Durante","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Antonio, Carlo, Domenic, Carmine, Gennaro, Sal, Amedeo, Ciro, Concetta, Egidio.","Italian: from the medieval personal name <i>Durante</i>, ultimately from the Latin verb <i>durare</i> ‘to last or endure’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Durand Hotham was born about 1133, in Howden, Yorkshire, England, his father, William de Hotham, was 35 and his mother, Mrs. William de HOTHAM, was 31. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Durand Hotham. He died after 1175, in Harthill, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"about 1133–after 1175":"umbes 1133–pärast 1175","1133–1175":"1133–1175","1137–Female":"1137–Surnud","1158–1210":"1158–1210","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1104–Female":"1104–Surnud","1104":"1104","1137":"1137","1158":"1158","1100":"1100","1210":"1210","1133":"1133","1175":"1175","after 1175":"pärast 1175","about 1132":"umbes 1132","about 1133":"umbes 1133","England":"England","Hotham, Yorkshire, England":"Hotham, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Harthill, Yorkshire, England":"Harthill, Yorkshire, England","Howden, Yorkshire, England":"Howden, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1133–after 1175":"noin 1133–1175 jälkeen","1133–1175":"1133–1175","1137–Female":"1137–Kuollut","1158–1210":"1158–1210","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1104–Female":"1104–Kuollut","1104":"1104","1137":"1137","1158":"1158","110